	<subsection id="SubSec_DirectionAngles">
		<headers>
			<full>Definition of Direction Angles</full>
			<toc>Definition of Direction Angles</toc>
			<short>Definition</short>
		</headers>
		<subsection.body>
			<def type="Definition" id="Def_DirectionAngle">
				<para>Given a vector <latex>\mathbf{x}</latex> in <latex>\RNr[n]</latex>, and a number <latex>i</latex>, <latex>1 \leq i \leq n</latex>, the <latex>i</latex>-th direction angle of <latex>\mathbf{x}</latex> is
					<index.glossary>
						<term>direction angle</term>
						<info>
							<caption>Direction Angle</caption>
							<para>the angle between a given vector <latex>\mathbf{x}</latex> in <latex>\RNr[n]</latex> and one of the coordinate axes.</para>
						</info>
					</index.glossary>
				</para>
				
				<para align="center"><subordinate>
					<hot><latex>\omega_i\ :=\ \sphericalangle(\mathbf{e}_i,\mathbf{x})</latex></hot>
					<info>
						<caption>Read this as ...</caption>
						<para>&lsquo;omega i is defined to be the angle from <latex>\mathbf{e}_i</latex> and <latex>\mathbf{x}</latex>.</para>
					</info>
				</subordinate>
				</para>
			</def>
			
			<para>To compute direction angles we use the 
				<subordinate>
					<hot>dot product</hot>
					<info>
						<caption>What does the Dot Product have to do with Direction Angles?</caption>
						<para>Indeed, if <latex>\mathbf{x}</latex> and <latex>\mathbf{y}</latex> are nonzero vectors, we know that</para>
						<math.display>
							<latex>\mathbf{x} \bullet \mathbf{y} = | \mathbf{x} | | \mathbf{y} |\ \cos \sphericalangle( \mathbf{x} , \mathbf{y} )</latex>
						</math.display>
					</info>
				</subordinate>, as in proposition below.</para>
			<xi:include href="DirectionAngleCompute_Prop.xml"/>
		</subsection.body>
	</subsection>
	
	
